A: Here is the code to increment a value in a HashMap in Java:

```java
import java.util.HashMap;
import java.util.Map;

public class Main {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        Map<String, Integer> freq = new HashMap<>();
        String word = "example";
        Integer count = freq.get(word);
        if (count == null) {
            freq.put(word, 1);
        } else {
            freq.put(word, count + 1);
        }
    }
}
```

In this code, we first get the current count of the word from the map. If the word is not in the map, we put it with a count of 1. If the word is already in the map, we increment its count by 1 and put it back into the map.

This code uses the `Map.get(Object key)` method to get the current count of the word, and the `Map.put(K key, V value)` method to put the word and its new count back into the map.

Please note that this code is case sensitive. If you want to count "example" and "Example" as the same word, you should convert the word to lower case or upper case before getting its count from the map.

Also, if you want to count words in a case-insensitive manner, you can convert the word to lower case or upper case before getting its count from the map.

